<p>Windows, for some time, has supported transactional interactions with files - using the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kernel_Transaction_Manager" rel="nofollow">Kernel Transaction Manager</a> (<a href="https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/aa366273(v=vs.85).aspx" rel="nofollow">MS KTM</a>) and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transactional_NTFS" rel="nofollow">Transactional NTFS</a>.  These features facilitate transactional changes to files on a local file system.</p>  <p>Does Linux/Unix have equivalent features?  Are there any published performance comparisons?</p>